5","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1189":"1189","1293":"1293","1218":"1218","Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England":"Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England","Studham, Bedfordshire, England":"Studham, Bedfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Inge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from the district of <i>Ing</i> (Essex), now represented by the placenames <i>Ingrave</i>, <i>Ingatestone</i>, <i>Fryerning</i>, <i>Margaretting</i>, and <i>Mountnessing</i>, as well as earlier alternative names of Fouchers (in East Hornden) and Buttsbury. The placename means ‘people of the district’, from Old English <i>gē</i> ‘district, region’ + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i>.","English: from Middle English <i>Inge</i>, itself either from the Old Norse female personal name <i>Inga</i> (a pet form of such names as <i>Ingi(v)aldr</i>), or from the Scandinavian male personal name <i>Inge</i> (a pet form of such names as <i>Ingiríthr</i>), or the Anglo-Saxon form of such a name, <i>Inga</i>. Unless there are other indications of gender, the two sources cannot be distinguished.","German: probably from the ancient Germanic female personal name <i>Inga</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Ing","meanings":["English (Buckinghamshire and Middlesex): variant of   Inge  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): nickname from Yiddish <i>ing</i> ‘young’.","Chinese: alternative Cantonese form of the surnames 應, 嬴, and 英, see   Ying   1-3."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":26,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":35,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":70,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Inge was born in 1189, in Studham, Bedfordshire, England as the son of William Inge I. He had at least 1 son. He died in Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1189–":"1189–Surnud","1189–Male":"1189–Surnud","1218–1246":"1218–1246","1148–1189":"1148–1189","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1189":"1189","1293":"1293","1218":"1218","Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Redbourn, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England":"Redbourn, Hertfordshire, England","Studham, Bedfordshire, England":"Studham, Bedf